{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b6d02168-9195-429d-ad88-0bc107814b26","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- The lambda receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS).\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85c5e8af-838b-4909-9299-62240096d990","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"A84D:2AD648:691772:793A74:69FBE2E8"},"id":"9e712faf-3363-43b8-9a3a-37df6084e6d0","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:55:11.316Z","parentId":"f70f1367-e757-46b9-b013-ed83d06c3657"}
